 \ul Plessis\ul0 's case that every magistrate's court in the country is competent to enterain any action against the State, provided only that the claim in issue is within the \expndtw12 limits\expndtw0  of the jurisdiction of such court, can no longer be regarded as valid, and that the question}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5034\fi0\ri0\sb798\sa0\tldot\tx7440 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 whether/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3141\margrsxn626\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li24\fi7422\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 49 whether the respondent in the present case was entitled to sue the appellant in the magistrate's court in Cape Town must accordingly be determined by reference to the provisions of sec. 28 of the Magistrates' Courts Act No. 32 of 1944. I now' proceed to consider that question.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi2472\ri0\sb6\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The \ul court\ul0  a \ul quo\ul0 , as I have said above, held that the respondent was entitled to sue the appellant in the magistrate's court in Cape Town on the ground that the State carries on business (as meant in sec. 28(1)(a) of the aforesaid Act) everywhere in South Africa, and accordingly also in the magisterial}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5412\fi0\ri0\sb918\sa0\tldot\tx7692 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 district/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3099\margrsxn1160\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\qr\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-3\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 50}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb114\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 district of Cape Town. (In view of that finding the court a \ul quo\ul0  found it unnecessary to deal with Du \ul Plessis\ul0 's case, \ul supra)\ul0 . The business carried on by the State everywhere in the country, the court a quo held, is that of governing the country. In coming to the conclusion - a finding that was supported by counsel for the respondent in this court - the court a \ul quo\ul0  relied on the judgment of Lord Diplock in the English case of \ul Town Investments Ltd and others v\ul0 . \ul Department of Environment\ul0 , (1977) 1 All E.R. 813. The issue in that case was whether certain premises were during a certain period the subject of a}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5394\fi0\ri0\sb816\sa0\tldot\tx7650 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "business/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3120\margrsxn935\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7320\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-9\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 51}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "business tenancy" within the meaning of two statutory "counter-inflation" orders. The buildings concerned were hired by the Government and were used as offices for civil servants employed in various government departments. The answer to the aforesaid question turned on the question whether the buildings could be said to be occupied by the tenant "for the purposes of a business carried on by him." (These words appeared in the two statutory rules). Lord Diplock (with whom Lord Simon of Glaisdale, Lord Kilbrandon and Lord Edmund-Davies agreed, Lord Morris of Borth-Y-Oest dissenting) said \ul inter alia\ul0  (the passage is}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5256\fi0\ri0\sb792\sa0\tldot\tx7512 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 referred/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3129\margrsxn488\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7470\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-9\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 52}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li42\fi0\ri0\sb690\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 referred to in the Judgment of the court a \ul quo\ul0 ) :}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2262\fi0\ri0\sb528\sa0\sl-480\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "The answer to this question depends on how broad a meaning is to be ascribed to the word 'business' in the definition of 'business tenancy' in the two counter-inflation orders. The word 'business' is an etymological chameleon; it suits its meaning to the,context in which it is found. It is not a term of legal art and its dictionary meanings as Lindley LJ pointed out in \ul Rolls v. Miller\ul0 , ((1884) 27 Ch. D. 71 at 88) embrace 'almost anything which is an occupation, as distinguished from a pleasure -anything which is an occupation or duty which requires attention is a business...'".}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb96\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Lord Diplock proceeded to hold that the "activities}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li6\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 of government" carried on in the leased premises by}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li18\fi0\ri0\sb6\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 servants of the Crown could properly be described as}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5016\fi0\ri0\sb810\sa0\tldot\tx7674 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 'business"/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3138\margrsxn383\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi7566\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 53 "business", and that "in exercising the functions of government the civil servants of the Crown were all carrying on a single business on behalf of the Crown." There can be little doubt, I think, that the meaning that was assigned to the word "business" in the aforesaid case is not the ordinary, or usual, meaning of the word, and it is therefore somewhat surprising that the court a \ul quo\ul0  should have been content to base its finding as to the meaning of the expression "carries on business" in sec. 28(1)(a) of the Magistrates' Courts Act on Lord Diplock's judgment without having any regard to the Afrikaans version of the section.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4950\fi0\ri0\sb918\sa0\tldot\tx6792 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3066\margrsxn557\margtsxn1103\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi7434\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 54 The Act, it may be added, was signed in Afrikaans. When there is any uncertainty as to the meaning of a word or expression in, say, the English version of a statutory provision, a consideration of the other -Afrikaans - version may serve to remove that uncertainty. See generally \ul Peter v. Peter and Other's\ul0 , 1959(2) S.A. 347(A.) at p. 350 D, and \ul S.v. Moroney\ul0 ,1978(4) S.A. 389 (A.) at pp. 408E-409A. The Afrikaans text of sec. 28(1)(a) reads that a magistrate's court has jurisdiction in respect of "'n persoon wat in die distrik woon, besigheid dryf of in diensbekrekking is", and there can be little doubt that the expression "besigheid dryf", in its ordinary meaning, is inappropriate to}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5976\fi0\ri0\sb936\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 describe/...}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3123\margrsxn668\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi7278\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 55 describe the carrying on of the functions of government. The authoritative \ul Woordeboek van die Afrikaanse Taal\ul0 , referring to the expression "'n besigheid dryf", states that "besigheid" means "handelsaak, winkel, bedryf", or "handelsbedrywighede".. It is clear, in my opinion, that "besigheid bedryf" has a commercial connotation, and that it cannot have the meaning that was assigned to the expression "carries on business" by the court a \ul quo\ul0 .}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li6\fi2466\ri0\sb6\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Counsel for the respondent contended; in the alternative to his main argument, in which he supported the finding of the court a \ul quo\ul0  as to the}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5526\fi0\ri0\sb912\sa0\tldot\tx7662 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 meaning/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3069\margrsxn560\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi7290\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 56 meaning of the expression "carries on business", that the State carries on business in the ordinary, commercial sense of the expression (e.g., by providing transport services, and by selling bonus bonds through its post offices), and that it does so everywhere in the Republic. The same argument was, it would seem, advanced in the court a \ul quo\ul0 , but the court did not deal with it.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi2478\ri360\sb0\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 It is nob wholly clear to me that it can properly be said that the State carries on business in the ordinary, i.e., commercial, sense of the expression (cf. the remark of Solomon, J.A., in}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4668\fi0\ri0\sb906\sa0\tldot\tx7662 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\ul\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Du Plessis\ul0 's{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3222\margrsxn845\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7440\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 57}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Du \ul Plessis\ul0 's case that "the King .... cannot be said to carry on business"), although I appreciate that it may be contended that the legislature, in providing that "person" in sec. 28(1) of the Magistrates' Courts Act includes "the State", intended that the State should, for the purposes of determining jurisdiction, be considered to be a person capable of carrying on business. I do not find it necessary to enter upon a discussion of this question, however, for even if one were obliged to hold that the State should, for jurisdictional purposes, be deemed to be a person capable of carrying on business, I would find}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4698\fi0\ri0\sb918\sa0\tldot\tx6504 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 the/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3105\margrsxn494\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7476\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 58}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 the proposition that it must be held to carry on business everywhere in the Republic, and that it can therefore be sued in any magistrate's court in the country, no matter where the relevant cause of action arose, wholly unacceptable. I am of the opinion that one should, on the grounds of convenience and in the interests of certainty, adopt a rule similar to that which the courts apply when determining the forum in which a trading corporation or other artificial person may be sued. In \ul Sciacero & Co v. Central South African Railways\ul0 , 1910 T.S. 119, a case in which the appellant had instituted an action against the}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5250\fi0\ri0\sb804\sa0\tldot\tx7656 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 respondent/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2783\margrsxn360\margtsxn1358\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7440\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-948\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-3\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 59}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li30\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-948\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 respondent in the magistrate's court at Belfast for}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li12\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-948\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 the value of goods that had not been delivered and}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-948\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 for a refund of railage paid thereon, Innes C.J.,}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb570\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 said \ul inter alia\ul0  (at p. 121) :}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2460\fi0\ri0\sb528\sa0\sl-480\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 "The general rule with regard to the bringing of fictions is \ul actor sequitur forum rei\ul0 . The plaintiff ascertains where the defendant resides, goes to his forum, and serves him with the summons there. And corporations are held to reside at the place where their head office is, and where the general supervision of their business is carried on. Hut the Magistrates' Court Proclamation renders a defendant liable to be sued not only where he resides, but where he carries on business; and the point we have to decide is whether the railway administration 'carries on business' at Belfast.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5094\fi0\ri0\sb1020\sa0\tldot\tx6780 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn5598\margrsxn797\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4968\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-3\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 60}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb534\sa0\sl-480\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The magistrate has held that it does not. In the widest sense, no doubt, the administration does 'carry on business' at Belfast. It conveys passengers and goods to and from that place, receives revenue there, has servants and agents on the spot, and transacts at that station, as at every other branch station, certain business which it is constituted to deal with. But the words can hardly be taken in their widest sense, because of the serious inconvenience \expndtw23 which\expndtw0  would follow in the case of great bodies like railway administrations, which have agencies and branch offices in numerous parts of the country, if they were sued not at the place where the management is situated, and where an explanation of the matters in dispute could be given, but at any \expndtw-10 small station where any of their \expndtw-12 officials reside and service could \expndtw0 be effected."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li3360\fi0\ri0\sb540\sa0\tldot\tx5046 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 This/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3252\margrsxn791\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi7068\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 61 This decision was cited with approval in \ul T.W. Beckett & Co. Ltd. v. H. Kroomer, Ltd\ul0 ., 1912 A.D. 324, where this court (at p. 334) referred to a number of English cases in which it was held that trading and railway corporations reside or carry on their business at the place where their chief office is situated, and that the locality of that office determines the forum in which alone the company is justiciable. See also \ul Estate Kootcher v. Commissioner for Inland Revenue\ul0 , 1941 A.D. 256, where Watermeyer J.A., delivering the judgment of the Court, referred to \ul Beckett\ul0 's case, \ul supra\ul0 , and pointed out (at p. 261)}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5262\fi0\ri0\sb930\sa0\tldot\tx6936 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 that/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3381\margrsxn836\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li12\fi7128\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 62 \expndtw0 that in a number of English cases, cited by him, the phrase "the place where the corporation carries on business" was used not in its popular sense, but in the sense of "the place where the central management and control actually abides."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi2316\ri0\sb12\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The considerations which move the courts to restrict, for jurisdictional purposes, the "residence" or "place of business" of a trading corporation to the place where the central management of such corporation is exercised, apply with equal, and even greater, force to the case of the State, considering its vast and country-wide activities.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4974\fi0\ri0\sb924\sa0\tldot\tx7092 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 In/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3282\margrsxn623\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7326\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 63}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li30\fi0\ri408\sb120\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 In the case of the State that place is Pretoria, which is, according to sec. 23 of the Republic of South Africa Constitution Act No. 32 of 1961, "the seat of Government of the Republic."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi2484\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 I should point out in conclusion that the court a \ul quo\ul0 , in holding that the State carries on business everywhere in the Republic and that the respondent was therefore entitled to sue it in the magistrate's court in Cape Town, expressed the view that if the Government was inconvenienced by being sued in that court, it could have applied for a transfer of the case to the magistrate's court at}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4824\fi0\ri0\sb1146\sa0\tldot\tx7242 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Hermanns/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn2969\margrsxn360\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi7140\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 64 Hermanns, where the respondent's cause of action arose. In saying this, the court referred to sec. 35(1) of the Magistrates' Courts Act of 1944 which provides that a court in which an action has been instituted may, on application made to it, transfer the case to another court if it is shown that it would cause the applicant "undue expense or inconvenience" if the action were to proceed in the court in which it was instituted. If the court a \ul quo\ul0  intended to indicate that in its opinion the existence of this provision was a good reason for holding that a plaintiff should be permitted to sue the State in any magistrate's}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5550\fi0\ri0\sb924\sa0\tldot\tx7524 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 court/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3279\margrsxn626\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li6\fi7140\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 65 court in the Republic, then I disagree with it. The relief which sec. 35(1) may afford the State in a particular case cannot in my opinion weigh up against the considerations which argue in favour of the adoption of a rule which would \expndtw12 limit,\expndtw0  as indicated above, the forum in which the State may be sued.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi2802\ri384\sb0\sa0\sl-960\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 In view of the aforegoing I am of the opinion that the appellant's special plea should have been upheld, and the following order is accordingly made :}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li30\fi0\ri0\sb6\sa0\sl-960\slmult0\tx2328 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-16\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22  (1)\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li30\fi0\ri0\sb6\sa0\sl-960\slmult0\tx2328 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent2298\pnf2{\pntxtb (}{\pntxta )}}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-16\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The appeal is upheld with costs.}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li30\fi0\ri0\sb6\sa0\sl-960\slmult0\tx2328 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-18\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22  (2)\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li30\fi0\ri0\sb6\sa0\sl-960\slmult0\tx2328 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent2298\pnf2{\pntxtb (}{\pntxta )}}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-18\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The order of the court a \ul quo\ul0  is set}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5100\fi0\ri0\sb1044\sa0\tldot\tx7224 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 aside/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3261\margrsxn1076\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2334\fi4956\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-954\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-3\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 66 \expndtw0 aside and the following order is substituted therefor : "The appeal is upheld with costs, and the order of the magistrate's court is altered to read : 'The defendant's special plea is upheld with costs'."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4818\fi0\ri768\sb618\sa0\sl-486\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\ul\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 P. J. RABIE \ul0 CHIEF JUSTICE.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li6\fi0\ri3828\sb990\sa0\sl-456\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 CORBETT, JA. KOTZE, JA. TRENGOVE, JA. Concur.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb234\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 VILJOEN, JA.}\par }